:"1594","Benington, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Benington, Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Benington, Hertfordshire, England":"Benington, Hertfordshire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1502–":"1502–Deceased","1510–Female":"1510–Deceased","1525–1594":"1525–1594","1502–Male":"1502–Deceased","1525":"1525","1502":"1502","1544":"1544","1510":"1510","1594":"1594","Benington, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Benington, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Benington, Hertfordshire, England":"Benington, Hertfordshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hodge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Suffolk): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hogge</i>, a rhyming pet form of   Roger  . In <i>The Canterbury Tales</i>, Chaucer's cook, ‘highte <i>Hogge</i> of Ware’, is invoked ‘Now tell on, <i>Roger</i> …’. Since Middle English spellings of the personal name are often impossible to distinguish from the nickname <i>Hog(ge)</i> ‘hog’, some early examples may be variants of   Hogg  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Roger","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Philippe, Alcee, Armand, Laurent, Leonce, Marcel, Yves, Clovis, Fernand, Gilberte, Janvier, Jean Claude.","Scottish, English, North German, French, Walloon, Catalan, and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘renown’ +<i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’, which was introduced into England by the Normans in the form <i>Rog(i)er</i> and was reinforced by the Old Norse cognate <i>Hróthgeirr</i>.","History: Gabriel Roger from Sainte-Verge in Deux-Sèvres, France, married Marie (de) Lacour in Quebec City, QC, in 1669. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Hodges","meanings":["English: variant of   Hodge   with genitival or post-medieval <i>-s</i>. Occasionally, however, the name may be topographic for a person who lived or worked at the house of someone named <i>Hodge</i> or <i>Roger</i>."]},{"name":"Hodgetts","meanings":["English (West Midlands): variant of <b>Hodgett</b>, with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, from a suffixed diminutive of the personal name <i>Hogge</i> (see   Hodge  )."]},{"name":"Hodgson","meanings":["English (northern): from the Middle English personal name   Hodge   + <i>-son</i>."]},{"name":"Hodgkin","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ho(d)gkin</i>, a pet form of <i>Hodge</i> + <i>-kin</i> (see   Hodge  )."]},{"name":"Hosty","meanings":["Irish (Mayo and Galway) and Welsh: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Oiste</b> or <b>Mac Coiste</b>, a patronymic from a Gaelicized form of the English personal name   Hodge  , originally borne by a Welshman, Hodge Merrick, who lived in Mayo in the 13th century. Members of this family settled in the area of <i>Gleann Hoiste</i> (Glenhest), Mayo, which retains the Gaelicized form <i>Hoiste</i> for   Hodge  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"M Hodge was born in 1502, in England, United Kingdom. He married F Hodge in 1544, in Benington, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1502–":"1502–Surnud","1510–Female":"1510–Surnud","1525–1594":"1525–1594","1502–Male":"1502–Surnud","1525":"1525","1502":"1502","1544":"1544","1510":"1510","1594":"1594","Benington, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Benington, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Benington, Hertfordshire, England":"Benington, Hertfordshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1502–":"1502–Kuollut","1510–Female":"1510–Kuollut","1525–1594":"1525–1594","1502–Male":"1502–Kuollut","1525":"1525","1502":"1502","1544":"1544","1510":"1510","1594":"1594","Benington